Thank you for choosing to participate in this study. Please read the consent form below.

 
Research Consent Form, The National Key Laboratory of Cognitive Neuroscience and Learning, Beijing Normal University 


Purpose:

This survey investigates people’s perception of social relationships.



Procedure:

You are invited to complete a questionnaire consisting of about 12 questions and some demographic information questions.



Risks and Side Effects:

There is no risk or side effect. Benefits: By completing this questionnaire, you will receive a monetary reward.



Confidentiality:

The results of this study may be published in an academic journal/book or used for teaching purposes, relevant scientific data may be shared to other researchers for further analysis.

However, your name or other identifiers will not be used in any publication or teaching materials without your specific permission.



Do you consent to participate in this study?

" Valence " Evaluation



Definition: A relationship is ‘Cooperative’ if both groups (a) have a common interest or goal, (b) like each other, (c) benefit from the relationship, (d) think alike or have similar views. Otherwise, the relationship is ‘Competitive’.

Examples: "Collaborative/Friendly" (e.g., parents-children) vs. "Competitive/Hostile" (e.g., between competitors).



How well do you understand this dimension? - level of understanding

"Equality" Evaluation



Definition: A relationship is ‘Equal’ if both groups (a) have the same social status, (b) are at the same level of power, control and competence, (c) share similar responsibilities, or have the same role. Otherwise, the relationship is ‘Hierarchical’.



Examples: "Equal" (e.g., paternal relatives - maternal relatives) vs. "Hierarchical" (e.g., parents - children). - level of understanding

"Activity Intensity" Evaluation



Definition: A relationship is activity ‘Intense’ if both groups (a) interact with each other frequently, (b) engage in a variety of activities, (c) know each other very well, (d) or spend long time together. Otherwise, the relationship is activity ‘Superficial’.



Examples: "Intense" (e.g., parents and children) vs. "Superficial" (e.g., visitors-receptionists). - level of understanding

column186:
"Sociemotional" Evaluation



Definition: A relationship is ‘Socioemotional’ if both groups (a) interact socially based on personal and familial ties, or (b) are emotionally intimate and pleasure-oriented. Otherwise, the relationship is ‘Task-oriented/Intellectual’, which emphasizes more on business, service-wise, and occupational associations.



Examples: "Sociemotional " (e.g., grandparents-grandchildren) vs. "Task-Oriented/ Intellectual" (e.g., interviewers-job applicants). - level of understanding

Examples: "Formal" (e.g., doctors-patients) vs. "Informal" (e.g., parents-children). - level of understanding
